ance for data, and Python specifically for AI.\n\n*   **Frontend (The Visuals):** Tauri + React (TypeScript). Utilizing HTML5 Canvas, SVG, and advanced CSS to render photorealistic, high-framerate gauges and interactive graphs.\n*   **Backend (The Engine):** Rust (via Tauri). Handles the AmbientWeather WebSocket stream, raw performance, and manages the local SQLite database seamlessly.\n*   **AI/Data Engine (The Oracle):** Python (running as a sidecar/microservice). Used specifically for crunching the 17-year historical dataset and interfacing with Local/Cloud LLMs for predictive modeling.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Phases\n\n### Phase 1: The Bermuda Fish Tank (Live Data MVP)\n*   Initialize Tauri + React + Rust workspace.\n*   Implement AmbientWeather WebSocket connection in Rust.\n*   Build the frontend photorealistic UI components (barograph drum, wind dials).\n*   Stream live data into the visual UI.\n\n### Phase 2: The Memory Bank (Local Recording)\n*   Integrate SQLite into the Rust backend.\n*   Define the `Readings` and `DailySummaries` schema.\n*   Automatically record live WebSocket packets to the database.\n*   Update the \"Fish Tank\" to display today's live extremes.\n\n### Phase 3: The Time Machine (Historical Ingestion)\n*   Build Rust/Python importers for legacy data sources.\n*   Source A: Cumulus legacy files (`dayfile.txt`, `*log.txt`) from 2009+.\n*   Source B: EasyWeatherIP `.mdb` databases.\n*   Implement data merging and conflict resolution to create a single, unified 17-year timeline.\n\n### Phase 4: The Analyst (Deep Dive UI)\n*   Build the secondary analytical UI in React.\n*   Integrate high-performance charting libraries.\n*   Implement calculations: Wind Run, NOAA-style monthly reports, Heat Index, Wind Chill.\n*   Allow user to scrub through the entire historical database.\n\n### Phase 5: The Oracle (AI Forecasting)\n*   Integrate the Python AI Sidecar.\n*   Feed 17 years of hyper-local Mount Soledad data into predictive models or LLM context windows.\n*   Generate plain-English, micro-climate specific weather briefings (e.g., predicting the marine layer based on historical pressure drop correlations)."},"result":[{"functionResponse":{"id":"write_file_1778351273045_2","name":"write_file","response":{"output":"Successfully created and wrote to new file: G:\\Dev\\CumulusAI\\CumulusAI_Vision_and_Architecture_v2.md. Here is the updated code:\n# CumulusAI: Vision & Architecture (v2)\r\n\r\n**Location**: Mount Soledad, La Jolla, CA\r\n**Current Station**: Ambient Weather WS-1002-WiFi\r\n**Data Lineage**: 2009 - Present (17 years of hyper-local data)\r\n\r\n## The Core Vision\r\nCumulusAI is a dual-mode weather application designed to be both a mesmerizing, photorealistic ambient display and a hardcore data-analysis tool, capped off with hyper-local AI forecasting capabilities.\r\n\r\n### Mode 1: The \"Bermuda Fish Tank\"\r\nA highly aesthetic, skeuomorphic \"instrument panel\" designed to be left on screen. Inspired by classic analog weather instruments (like brass barographs with rotating paper drums, glass reflections, and physical-looking dials).\r\n\r\n### Mode 2: The \"Analyst\"\r\nA data-dense, modern analytical interface for deep-diving into 17 years of historical weather data. Features massive scrubbable charts, extremes tracking, and specialized calculations like \"Wind Run.\"\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## The Technology Stack\r\n\r\nMoving away from pure Python/PyQt to leverage modern web rendering for graphics, native performance for data, and Python specifically for AI.\r\n\r\n*   **Frontend (The Visuals):** Tauri + React (TypeScript). Utilizing HTML5 Canvas, SVG, and advanced CSS to render photorealistic, high-framerate gauges and interactive graphs.\r\n*   **Backend (The Engine):** Rust (via Tauri). Handles the AmbientWeather WebSocket stream, raw performance, and manages the local SQLite database seamlessly.\r\n*   **AI/Data Engine (The Oracle):** Python (running as a sidecar/microservice). Used specifically for crunching the 17-year historical dataset and interfacing with Local/Cloud LLMs for predictive modeling.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## Implementation Phases\r\n\r\n### Phase 1: The Bermuda Fish Tank (Live Data MVP)\r\n*   Initialize Tauri + React + Rust workspace.\r\n*   Implement AmbientWeather WebSocket connection in Rust.\r\n*   Build the frontend photorealistic UI components (barograph drum, wind dials).\r\n*   Stream live data into the visual UI.\r\n\r\n### Phase 2: The Memory Bank (Local Recording)\r\n*   Integrate SQLite into the Rust backend.\r\n*   Define the `Readings` and `DailySummaries` schema.\r\n*   Automatically record live WebSocket packets to the database.\r\n*   Update the \"Fish Tank\" to display today's live extremes.\r\n\r\n### Phase 3: The Time Machine (Historical Ingestion)\r\n*   Build Rust/Python importers for legacy data sources.\r\n*   Source A: Cumulus legacy files (`dayfile.txt`, `*log.txt`) from 2009+.\r\n*   Source B: EasyWeatherIP `.mdb` databases.\r\n*   Implement data merging and conflict resolution to create a single, unified 17-year timeline.\r\n\r\n### Phase 4: The Analyst (Deep Dive UI)\r\n*   Build the secondary analytical UI in React.\r\n*   Integrate high-performance charting libraries.\r\n*   Implement calculations: Wind Run, NOAA-style monthly reports, Heat Index, Wind Chill.\r\n*   Allow user to scrub through the entire historical database.\r\n\r\n### Phase 5: The Oracle (AI Forecasting)\r\n*   Integrate the Python AI Sidecar.\r\n*   Feed 17 years of hyper-local Mount Soledad data into predictive models or LLM context windows.\r\n*   Generate plain-English, micro-climate specific weather briefings (e.g., predicting the marine layer based on historical pressure drop correlations)."}}}],"status":"success","timestamp":"2026-05-09T18:28:00.069Z","resultDisplay":{"fileDiff":"Index: CumulusAI_Vision_and_Architecture_v2.md\n===================================================================\n--- CumulusAI_Vision_and_Archi