{"id":"6db36554-8bd2-42bb-866b-0b98057db081","timestamp":"2026-05-09T18:48:14.101Z","type":"gemini","content":"You are absolutely right. The \"MyXXXX\" / \"XXXX_AI\" era is definitely a phase we can skip. **SoledadWX** is clean, professional, and timeless. \n\nAnd yes, changing the root folder *now* is the smartest thing you can do. Once Tauri initializes, it weaves the folder names into package namespaces, bundle identifiers, and configuration files. It is much harder to change later.\n\n**Don't worry about breaking our continuity!** My memory of our entire conversation, our 5-phase plan, and the photorealistic UI vision is held safely in my active context right now. \n\nHere is the best way to handle the rename without upsetting Windows' file locking:\n\n1. Open **File Explorer** (or a separate PowerShell window).\n2. Navigate to `G:\\Dev\\` and rename the `CumulusAI` folder to `SoledadWX`.\n3. (If Windows complains that the folder is \"in use\", it's because this CLI session is currently running inside it. If that happens, it is perfectly safe to type `/exit` here, rename the folder, open your terminal in the new `SoledadWX` folder, and launch me again. Depending on your CLI settings, you can usually resume the session, but even if we start a \"new\" chat, I have already written the `CumulusAI_Vision_and_Architecture_v2.md` file! We can just rename that file to `SoledadWX_Architecture.md` and pick up exactly where we left off).\n\nTry renaming it in File Explorer first. If it works, just reply \"Done!\" and I will immediately start using `G:\\Dev\\SoledadWX` for all my future commands and we will initialize Tauri!","thoughts":[],"tokens":{"input":70330,"output":368,"cached":68029,"thoughts":0,"tool":0,"total":70698},"model":"gemini-3.1-pro-preview"}
